content:
Defined the mini coding-agent v0.1 shape from the two references and Ariadne’s local-first ticket-centered boundary. I did not edit files, commit, push, create a PR, or create child issues; the build issues below are draft issue specs for the backlog.

## What the references imply

`mini-swe-agent` says the useful core can be very small: a linear model loop, a local execution environment, bounded cost/step/time limits, simple command execution, append-only trajectory, and a clear completion signal. Its strongest lesson is not “many tools”; it is that the harness should be inspectable and recoverable.

`cc-mini` adds the product affordances a builder expects around that loop: explicit tools, read-only tools auto-approved, writes/bash permission-gated, local session persistence, context compaction, plan/read-only mode, optional sandboxing, and later coordinator/worker expansion. For Ariadne v0.1, most of that should be staged as capabilities around TicketAssignment and AgentRun, not as a standalone Claude Code clone.

## Proposed v0.1 architecture

Plain shape:

1. BuildTicket is the work carrier.
2. A human or backlog update assigns a ticket to an AgentProfile, creating a TicketAssignment.
3. The local daemon claims one queued assignment and starts an AgentRun.
4. The run builds a compact handoff from the ticket, BuildPacket, target repo, runtime capability snapshot, and selected skills.
5. A backend adapter executes the run locally: fake-codex first, real Codex/Claude only behind existing explicit execution gates.
6. The run records progress events, model/tool transcript or trajectory, changed files/diff, test output, blocker or completion summary, and next-ticket suggestions as local artifacts/comments.
7. The Workbench shows the run timeline and evidence packet on the ticket.

Keep in v0.1:
- linear local run loop and persisted trajectory;
- one assignment claimed at a time;
- explicit runtime/resource snapshot;
- permission/default-off external execution;
- typed blocker/failure reason;
- local diff/test/review evidence;
- browser-visible ticket comments and run status.

Defer:
- hosted server clone, Postgres, multi-workspace auth, WebSockets, cloud runtime fleet;
- automatic commit/push/merge/PR creation;
- multi-agent coordinator mode;
- full memory consolidation and companion-style UX;
- generic tool ecosystem beyond what the ticket runtime needs.

## First 3 build issues

### 1. Minimal TicketAssignment -> AgentRun execution kernel

Build the smallest local daemon path that claims one queued TicketAssignment, creates an AgentRun, writes lifecycle events, invokes a backend adapter, and persists a trajectory/artifact directory.

Acceptance:
- queued assignment becomes claimed/running/done, blocked, or failed;
- AgentRun stores lifecycle_state, failure_reason, blocker, started/finished timestamps, and artifact paths;
- fake backend can complete deterministically without external execution;
- every state transition appears in ticket comments/progress events;
- directory lock prevents concurrent runs on the same target repo.

### 2. Local coding backend adapter with gated real execution

Define a backend interface inspired by mini-swe-agent: prepare handoff, execute locally, capture transcript, collect diff/tests, return structured result. Wire fake-codex first and real Codex/Claude only when `ARIADNE_ENABLE_EXTERNAL_EXECUTION=1` plus explicit confirmation is present.

Acceptance:
- backend result schema includes status, summary, transcript path, diff path, changed files, tests run, failure reason, blocker, and suggested next tickets;
- missing login/quota/configuration returns `BLOCKED_WITH_EVIDENCE`, not a silent failure;
- no backend can commit, push, merge, or create PRs;
- command execution is bounded by timeout and local target path validation;
- unit tests cover success, blocked, failed, and execution-disabled paths.

### 3. Workbench ticket run timeline and evidence packet

Expose the v0.1 coding-agent loop in the browser ticket view: assignment status, active run status, progress comments, blocker, diff/test/review artifacts, and next-ticket suggestions.

Acceptance:
- assigning a ticket from the Workbench creates a queued assignment visible on the ticket;
- daemon/run progress updates are visible without reading files manually;
- completed run shows evidence packet links: handoff, transcript, diff, tests, review/blocker, next tickets;
- blocked run clearly names the missing gate/resource and maps to Inbox/Runtime behavior;
- UI stays local-only and does not expose raw shell execution controls.

## Blockers / missing resources

No blocking project resource was missing for this definition: both external reference repos were available and Ariadne’s local docs establish the ticket-centered boundary. The only product decision to pin before implementation is which real backend is first-class for v0.1 (`codex`, `claude-code`, or both behind the same adapter), but fake-codex can start the work without that decision.
